-- t12 A dedication to Zeus Helios Great Sarapis in honor of a desector on an ostracon from Mons Claudianus -- tPART III THE ROAD SYSTEM AND THE MAIL -- t13 An unpublished ostracon from the Eastern Desert and the provenance of O.Amst. 9 -- t14 Kaine, a new town: an experiment in familial reunification in the second century ad -- t15 The road system of the Eastern Desert of Egypt under the Early Empire in the light of the excavated ostraca -- t16 Collection of cases of irregularities in the transmission of official mail -- t17 The postal register of Turbo, curator of the praesidium of Xeron Pelagos -- t18 Men and gods in a network0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA detailed archaeological study of life in Egypt's Eastern desert during the Roman period by a leading scholarRome in Egypt’s Eastern Desert is a two-volume set collecting Hélène Cuvigny’s most important articles on Egypt’s Eastern desert during the Roman period. The fort excavations that she has directed have uncovered a wealth of material, including tens of thousands of texts written on pottery fragments (ostraca). Some of these are administrative texts, but many more are correspondence, both official and private, written by and to the people (mostly but not all men) who lived and worked in these remote and harsh environments, supported by an elaborate network of defense, administration and supply that tied the entire region together. The contents of Rome in Egypt’s Eastern Desert have all been published earlier in peer-reviewed venues, but almost entirely in French. All of the contributions have been translated by the editor and brought up to date with respect to bibliography and in some cases significantly rewritten by the author, in order to take account of the enormous amount of new material discovered in the intervening time and subsequent publications. A full index makes this body of work far more accessible than it was before. This book brings together thirty years of detailed study of this material, bringing to life the geography, administration, military, quarry operations, life in the forts, and the religion and expressive language of the population who lived in them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aOstrakazEgyptzEastern Desert. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aBagnall, Roger S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagnall, Roger S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishz978311075405608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021z9783110753813oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073910740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479810680423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479810680/original  a978-3-11-073910-7  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075405-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021